-- 
Oil Volatility Slips as Futures Rise From Month’s Lowest Level

-- B y   M a r g o t   H a b i b y
-- 
2011-04-13T20:21:24Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-13/oil-volatility-slips-as-underlying-futures-head-up-then-drop.html
Oil options volatility slipped as
the underlying front-month futures rose from the lowest level
this month.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
June, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a gauge
of options prices, was 29.9 percent as of 4 p.m. in  New York ,
down from 31.9 percent yesterday.  Oil for May delivery gained 86 cents, or 0.8 percent, to
settle at $107.11 a barrel on the  New York Mercantile Exchange .
Yesterday’s settlement of $106.25 was the lowest since March 30.  Prices tumbled 5.8 percent in the previous two sessions,
the biggest two-day drop since May. Futures have risen 27
percent in the past year.  The most active contracts in electronic trading as of 4
p.m. today were May $105 puts with 7,131 lots changing hands.
They dropped 64 cents to 19 cents a barrel. May $110 calls, the
next-most active contract, fell 18 cents to 7 cents a barrel
with 5,163 contracts trading. One contract is for 1,000 barrels
of oil.  May options expire tomorrow.  Nymex distributes real-time data for electronic trading and
releases information on floor trading, where the bulk of options
trading occurs, the next business day.  June $140 calls were the most active options traded in the
previous session, with 14,628 lots changing hands. They
decreased 7 cents to 17 cents a barrel. The next most active
option, May $105 puts, gained 68 cents to 83 cents a barrel on
13,918 lots.  Open interest was highest for June $150 calls with 42,615
contracts. Next were December 2012 $80 puts with 40,062 and
December $100 calls with 38,684.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Margot Habiby in  Dallas  at 
 mhabiby@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Dan Stets at   dstets@bloomberg.net . 